<section xml:id="C4.S9">
<title>Continued Fractions</title>         
<subsection xml:id="C4.S9.SS1">
<title>Logarithms</title>          
<para xml:id="C4.S9.SS1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C4.S9.SS1.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="4.9.1" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S9.E1">\ln\left(1+z\right)=\cfrac{z}{1+\cfrac{z}{2+\cfrac{z}{3+\cfrac{4z}{4+\cfrac{4z }{5+\cfrac{9z}{6+\cfrac{9z}{7+}}}}}}}\cdots, if |\operatorname{ph}\left(1+z\right)|&lt;\pi</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C4.S9.SS1.p1.s2">
<Math equation-number="4.9.2" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S9.E2">\ln\left(\frac{1+z}{1-z}\right)=\cfrac{2z}{1-\cfrac{z^{2}}{3-\cfrac{4z^{2}}{5- \cfrac{9z^{2}}{7-\cfrac{16z^{2}}{9-}}}}}\cdots,</Math> valid when <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S9.SS1.p1.m1">z\in\mathbb{C}\setminus(-\infty,-1]\cup[1,\infty)</Math> ; see Figure4.23.1(i).
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C4.S9.SS1.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C4.S9.SS1.p2.s1">
For other continued fractions involving logarithms seeLorentzen and Waadeland (1992, pp. 566–568).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C4.S9.SS1.p2.s2">
See also Cuyt et al. (2008, pp. 196–200).
</sentence>

</para>
  
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C4.S9.SS2">
<title>Exponentials</title>          
<para xml:id="C4.S9.SS2.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C4.S9.SS2.p1.s1">
For <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S9.SS2.p1.m1">z\in\mathbb{C}</Math> , <Math equation-number="4.9.3" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S9.E3">e^{z}=\cfrac{1}{1-\cfrac{z}{1+\cfrac{z}{2-\cfrac{z}{3+\cfrac{z}{2-\cfrac{z}{5+ \cfrac{z}{2-}}}}}}}\cdots=1+\cfrac{z}{1-\cfrac{z}{2+\cfrac{z}{3-\cfrac{z}{2+\cfrac{z}{5-\cfrac{z}{2+ \cfrac{z}{7-}}}}}}}\cdots=1+\cfrac{z}{1-(z/2)+\cfrac{z^{2}/(4\cdot 3)}{1+\cfrac{z^{2}/(4\cdot 15)}{1+ \cfrac{z^{2}/(4\cdot 35)}{1+}}}}\cdots\cfrac{z^{2}/(4(4n^{2}-1))}{1+}\cdots</Math> <Math equation-number="4.9.4" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S9.E4">e^{z}-e_{n-1}(z)={\cfrac{z^{n}}{n!-\cfrac{n!z}{(n+1)+\cfrac{z}{(n+2)-\cfrac{(n +1)z}{(n+3)+\cfrac{2z}{(n+4)-}}}}}\cfrac{(n+2)z}{(n+5)+\cfrac{3z}{(n+6)-}} \cdots},</Math> where <Math equation-number="4.9.5" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S9.E5">e_{n}(z)=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\frac{z^{k}}{k!}</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C4.S9.SS2.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="6" xml:id="C4.S9.SS2.p2.s1">
For other continued fractions involving the exponential function seeLorentzen and Waadeland (1992, pp. 563–564).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="7" xml:id="C4.S9.SS2.p2.s2">
See also Cuyt et al. (2008, pp. 193–195).
</sentence>

</para>
  
</subsection>
 
